<br>
  I spent an hour and a half today putting up the grocery order while the cashier stood there.  Didn't ask if I needed help with anything, didn't just start putting stuff away, didn't do anything but help customers.  I swear he didn't make coffee after 10am.  I'm sorry, but 4 hours is a little long to have a pot of coffee just sit there.<br>
<br>
  My day started off with the cashier who quit yesterday showing up in the morning.  I told him to clock out and go home.  He didn't quite get the concept.  I told him he had a choice of quitting, or being fired.  He started making excuses after I told him why he was terminated.  The same excuses he told me when he got written up for previous stuff.  I'm sorry, but there is no reason to have over $110 in your cash drawer.  Zero.  Especially after I've told you twice that it's a robbery risk, and you can be automatically terminated for having that much cash in your drawer.<br>
<br>
  So the punk says he needs to talk to my supervisor.  I AM THE MANAGER.  So he went to the store where my supervisor was doing paperwork, and was told exactly what I'd just told him.<br>
<br>
  Before the guy signs off on the register to leave there is an error message.  I find out that end of day has been run on only one register.  This means that I can't run any credit card transactions until it has been run on the register with the error message.  I call the help desk.  They say they need to escalate me to better techs, and they'll call me back.  They finally call, and can't manage to dial into our computer system.  So I find out that our computer isn't even hooked up to the phone line.  I had to unplug the fax line, find slack, and then pray I was plugging it into the correct spot on the hard drive.<br>
<br>
  At 9:30am I start on the rest of my paperwork that I needed from the computer in the office that also had the error message.  Normally, I'm done with the paperwork and deposit at that point.<br>
